JS Temporal Date Arithmetic:

- Temporal provides safe and clear methods for date arithmetic.
- You can add or subtract days, months, years, and more without modifying the original value.

#) Add Days:
    - Use the add() method to add days.
    - üí°The original date is not changed.
        // Create a Temporal object
        const myDate = Temporal.PlainDate.from('2026-05-17');

        // Add a duration
        const newDate = myDate.add({ days: 7 });    // 2026-05-24


#) Subtract Days:
    - Use subtract() to subtract time.
        // Create a Temporal object
        const myDate = Temporal.PlainDate.from('2026-05-17');

        // Subtract a duration
        const newDate = myDate.subtract({ days: 10 });   // 2026-05-07


#) JavaScript Temporal add():
    - The add() method returns a new date moved forward by a given duration.
    - Syntax: temporal.add(duration)

        // Create a Temporal object
        const myDate = Temporal.PlainDate.from('2026-05-17');
        // Add a duration
        const newDate = myDate.add({ days: 10 });   // 2026-05-27

        // Create a Temporal object
        const today = Temporal.Now.plainDateISO();  // 2026-02-26
        // Add a duration
        const nextWeek = today.add({ days: 7 });    // 2026-03-05

        // Create a Temporal object
        const today = Temporal.Now.plainDateISO();  // 2026-02-26
        // Add multiple units
        const newDate = today.add({ years: 1, months: 2, days: 15 });   // 2027-05-11
    
    - üí°You can add or subtract various time units using a duration object:
            years
            months
            weeks
            days
            hours
            minutes
            seconds
            milliseconds
            microseconds
            nanoseconds
    - üí°Unlike the legacy Date object, Temporal objects are immutable.
        Methods like until(), add(), or with() always return a new instance rather than modifying the
        existing one.


#) JavaScript Temporal subtract():
    - The subtract() method returns a new temporal object representing this date moved backward by a
        given duration.
    - Syntax: temporal.subtract(duration)
    - ‚úÖFrom a Temporal.PlainDate (a date without a time zone) you can subtract a full duration:
            // Create a Temporal object
            const myDate = Temporal.PlainDate.from('2026-05-17');
            // Subtract a duration
            const newDate = myDate.subtract({ days: 10 });   // 2026-05-07

            // Create a Temporal object
            const today = Temporal.Now.plainDateISO();      // 2026-02-26
            // Subtract a duration
            const lastWeek = today.subtract({ days: 6 });   // 2026-02-20
    
    - ‚ùåFrom a Temporal.Instant you can only subtract a fixed duration (hours, minutes, seconds) but
        not calendar durations like months or years, as their length can vary depending on the time
        zone and the calendar.
            // Create a Temporal.Instant object
            const now = Temporal.Instant.fromEpochMilliseconds(Date.now()); // 2026-02-26T13:06:01.239Z
            // Subtract 5 hours and 30 minutes
            const fiveHalfHoursAgo = now.subtract({ hours: 5, minutes: 30 });   // 2026-02-26T07:39:16.647Z


#) Add Months:
    - Temporal automatically handles different month lengths.
            const date = Temporal.PlainDate.from("2026-01-31");
            const result = date.add({ months: 1 });     // 2026-02-31
    
    - If the next month has fewer days, Temporal adjusts automatically.


#) Add Years:
    - Adding years works correctly, even for leap years.
            const date = Temporal.PlainDate.from("2024-02-29");
            const result = date.add({ years: 1 });      // 2025-02-28
    
    - Temporal handles leap year adjustments automatically.


#) The width() Method:
    - The width() method returns a new date with specific fields replaced.
            // Create a Temporal object
            const date = Temporal.PlainDate.from("2026-05-17"); 
            // Replace month and day
            const customDate = date.with({ month:12, day:25 }); // 2026-12-25


#) The compare() Method:
    - The compare() method returns -1 if the first date is earlier, 1 if it is later, and 0
        if they are equal:
            // Create two Temporal objects
            const date1 = Temporal.PlainDate.from("2026-05-17");
            const date2 = Temporal.PlainDate.from("2024-12-25");
            // Compare the dates
            result = Temporal.PlainDate.compare(date1, date2);  // 1
    
    - The compare() method is designed to be passed directly into the JavaScript Array.sort() method:
            // Create an Array of dates
            const dates = [
                Temporal.PlainDate.from("2026-05-17"),
                Temporal.PlainDate.from("2022-01-01"),
                Temporal.PlainDate.from("2024-12-25")
            ];
            // Sort chronologically
            dates.sort(Temporal.PlainDate.compare); // 2022-01-01,2024-12-25,2026-05-17
    
    - ‚ö†Ô∏èAlways use the equals() or compare() methods rather than standard equality operators.


#) The equals() Method:
    - returns true or false.
            // Create two Temporal objects
            const date1 = Temporal.PlainDate.from('2026-05-17');
            const date2 = Temporal.PlainDate.from('2026-05-17');
            let result = date1.equals(date2);   // true


#) Date Arithmetic with ZonedDateTime:
    - ZonedDateTime handles daylight saving time (DST) safely.
            const start = Temporal.ZonedDateTime.from("2026-03-29T00:00:00+01:00[Europe/Oslo]");
            const nextDay = start.add({ days: 1 }); // 2026-03-30T00:00:00+02:00[Europe/Oslo]
    
    - If a DST change occurs, Temporal adjusts automatically.


#) Compare with Date Arithmetic:
    - Date modifies the original object and may cause DST-related issues.
            const start = new Date("2026-02-17");
            start.setDate(start.getDate() + 10);    // Wed May 27 2026 05:45:00 GMT+0545 (Nepal Time)


#) Best Practices:
    üëâ Use PlainDate for date-only arithmetic.
    üëâ Use ZonedDateTime for time zone-aware calculations.
    üëâ Avoid manual millisecond calculations.
    üëâ Prefer immutable operations.